Author: hubsmoke
Content: Probably not the correct format for a bug report, but I describe the problem here: https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/issues/112

Author: hubsmoke
Content: It's possible I am also misunderstanding how StarkNet handles rejected transactions. Perhaps the status is the only thing that isn't reported, but subsequent valid transactions are included into the chain (without updating status). If so, this is not that bad. However if rejected transactions are blocked from being included on chain, this could potentially be abused by a malicious actor

Author: hubsmoke
Content: For example, if there is a particular account contract with a significant amount of trading activity, a malicious actor could spam the network with a range of possible parameters and nonces, but with an invalid signature and effectively block their trades. (creating many transaction hashes that won't get reprocessed)

Author: xjonathanlei
Content:
When querying `get_code` for a contract that doesn't exist, the feeder gateway returns:
```json
{"bytecode":[],"abi":{}}
```
Note that `abi` is now an object instead of an empty array. This is inconsistent with the response when the code exists: `abi` is an array.

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: I wonder if this is on purpose? If this is to differential between empty ABI (`[]`) vs non-existent ABI (`{}`) wouldn't it be better to use something like `null` or simply ignore the field?

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: Not exactly a bug, but currently the `deploy` command under `starknet` in `cairo-lang` **unnecessarily** includes `debug_info` in the compressed program.

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: Taking the OpenZeppelin's account contract for example, the compressed base64 representation of the program is **51,284** characters, and it gets reduced to **20,252** characters after getting rid of `debug_info`.

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: This behavior unnecessarily wastes bandwidth & compute power

Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content: You suggest changing the default deploy compilation to `--no_debug_info`?

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: ah didn't realize that exists but yes only for deployment. the default compilation output should definitely include it

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: I mean.. why include it in the request if it's useless to the server anyways

Author: ago#5957
Content:
There are some whacky things happening while looping through this sum. It really matters in what order the `iterator` and `sum` variables are instantiated and called, if they are called in a different order to how they are instantiated the program gets into a loop and times out, but it works when called in the same order.  Not sure if this is a bug or due to normal operation of how constants https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/how_cairo_works/consts.html are assigned
Code:
``` %builtins output
# Import the serialize_word() function.
from starkware.cairo.common.serialize import serialize_word

func main{output_ptr : felt*}():
    tempvar iterator = 10
    tempvar sum = 12   #sum should be before iterator otherwise will fail
    
    loop_start:
        tempvar sum = sum+1
        tempvar iterator = iterator -1
    jmp loop_start if iterator != 0
    
    serialize_word(sum)
    # Return.
    return ()
end```
Screenshots of what happens in the Cairo Playground:

Author: peteris.
Content:
possible issue with signatures, apologies if a duplicate:

- there is a known issue that transactions with the same arguments result in the same transaction hash
- however, if invoking an account contract, transactions with or without the signature also result in the same transaction hash and cannot be "overridden"

exploit scenario:
- user calls transaction, which fails, forgetting to apply a signature
- user attempts to use a signature with same transaction but the original failure cannot be amended
- user has to now pay for another transaction to bump up the nonce and re-issue the original transaction

Author: ggballas#4060
Content:
not a bug per se, but importing the `@starkware-industries/starkgate-contracts` lib to you node repo, and then importing libs in your Solidity code (e.g. `import "@starkware-industries/starkgate-contracts/src/starkware/starknet/apps/starkgate/solidity/StarknetERC20Bridge.sol";`) results in a `HH404: File not found` error when the solidity compiler tries to retrieve files imported by `StarknetERC20Bridge.sol` (or any other contract in the `starkgate-contracts` repo for that matter).

this is because the imports within the `starkgate-contracts` repo are absolute to the repo directory, instead of relative. it's a quick fix that will help developers. plz reach out to me if that explanation wasn't clear. üôè

Author: nic619
Content:
(I was not aware of this channel so I posted the message originally at dev-support channel and now repost it here)

Hi, I have a question regarding the L1->L2 message cancellation mechanism:
If I understand correctly, there should be a way to reset cancellation request time of a message? i.e., resetting `l1ToL2MessageCancellations()[msgHash]`
https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/4e233516f52477ad158bc81a86ec2760471c1b65/src/starkware/starknet/eth/StarknetMessaging.sol#L158-L159

Otherwise for the same `msgHash`, the cancellation only has to be requested and cancelled once and all future cancellation can happens immediately.

It might be used maliciously to cancel other user's or dapp's message by sending-and-cancelling message in advance (perhaps by predicting possible/popular message params `(toAddress, selector, payload, nonce)` etc.

And if the message can be instantly cancelled, it would also become an DoS attacking surface.

Author: daniel.kroeni
Content:
Hi, not sure if this is the right channel, but I wanted to report a small typo in the documentation on the following page:
https://starknet.io/documentation/contracts/#contract_abi
> h(...h(h(0,a[1)),a[2]),...,a[n]),n)
the above should more likely read:
`h(h(...h(h(0,a[1]),a[2]),...,a[n]),n)`

Author: daniel.kroeni
Content:
And on this page:
https://cairo-lang.org/docs/how_cairo_works/types.html#used-defined-type-aliases
"Used-defined" should read "User-defined".

Author: bigboys1
Content:
I see this as an error/missing that I will point out now:
1- First of all, I rented a server to run testnet. I have successfully completed the node installation steps. (via CMD) However, when I wanted to leave CMD/close my connection from the server (ctrl c) it disconnected me from INFURA even though I downloaded all the blocks, so no reguest data came. 

2- I thought I made a mistake during the installation phase and I deleted the server and reinstalled it. (My only shortcoming is SCREEN -S Main Page) Node successfully communicated with INFURA. However, after a certain time/about 10 hours, I realized that he lost contact with INFURA again. I don't know if node was running in the background but the solution was that I needed to reach the server and start "cargo run --release --bin pathfinder -- --ethereum.url https://mainnet.infura.io/ v3/****** It was because I ran the " command. But it works when cmd is open, when I close it, communication is lost.

***So, what I want to mention briefly is that when I want to exit the virtual server, there is a lack of communication in the node. I recommend you to review, especially Requests.*** @STARK Team

1) MintSquare

3) Myswap

Author: xenoliss
Content:
Hello there ! Not really a bug but I think I found a small typo issue while reading the cairo doc: https://starknet.io/docs/how_cairo_works/functions.html#return-values
> The Cairo compiler automatically creates constants named foo.Return.z and foo.Return.w with the values -1 and -2 respectively, so that [ap - 1] can be written as [ap + foo.Return.z]
Should be I guess:
> The Cairo compiler automatically creates constants named foo.Return.z and foo.Return.w with the values -2 and -1 respectively, so that [ap - 2] can be written as [ap + foo.Return.z]

Author: .prashantb
Content:
Hey Guys,

On this page there are few typos (please see below): https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/develop/Data_Availability/on-chain-data/

The state diffs contain information on every contact whose storage was updated and additional information on contract deployments. Those differences are sent as unit256[] array as part of the calldata, and are encoded as follows:

===> every contact --> should be "every contract"
===> unit256[] --> should be "uint256[]

Author: closer2282
Content:
Sorry for your inconvenience, StarkNet's a bit congested recently due to heavy load, but the team's working on it, and the performance will improve soon. Thanks for your support!
**Hi everyone!

StarkNet Alpha 0.10.2 will be released to integration on this Wednesday, 02/11

- This version introduces sequencer parallelization! This is the first step in our roadmap of performance upgrades. Details about the specific mechanism of parallelization and the roadmap in general will be released in a post next week.
- A new endpoint, estimate_fee_bulk, is added to the feeder gateway. This will allow estimating the fee of several transactions at once, where each transaction is executed relative to the resulting state from applying the previous one.

Additionally, as a temporary measure to handle the load on testnet, we created a new testnet environment, testnet2, which is also based on Goerli. See the announcement for more details https://starkware.notion.site/Update-to-Core-Stars-on-StarkNet-s-performance-temporary-solutions-Oct-27-2022-4e2d8a73f1d048f2b9e284ef47d14564. StarkNet Testnet1 & Testnet2 are expected to upgrade to 0.10.2 one week after integration, Wednesday 9/11. Mainnet is expected to be released a week after testnets, on the 15'th.**

Author: nine9#5720
Content:
Hello, I found a mistake in the starknet documentation, the sendMessageToL2 function of the L1 StartNet core contract should be called instead of send_message() when sending a message from the L1 contract to the L2 contract.
https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/getting_started/l1l2/#messages-from-l1-to-l2

Author: closer2282
Content:
Hi may i ask did you check the example in this docs?
https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/getting_started/l1l2/#an-example-of-a-simple-token-bridge

Author: nine9#5720
Content: The code in the example is correct, but there is an error in the text description here, suggest changing "the send_message() function of the Starknet core contract" to "the sendMessageToL2() function of the Starknet core contract".

Author: nine9#5720
Content: I think the text should be changed to prevent misleading other developers.

Author: closer2282
Content: Got it, thanks for the feedback!

Author: nine9#5720
Content: You're welcome, it's all for the good of the community, I'll keep up the good work.

Content: Hello guys. I found the problem when starknet deploy new account. But when executing `starknet deploy_account` to deploy the account again, it prompts "Error: AssertionError: Account '<account name>' for network 'alpha-goerli' is already deployed.". Content: The `deployed` status of this account in the `.starknet_accounts/starknet_open_zeppelin_accounts.json`  has changed to true. If you need to redeploy this account, you need to manually change it to false in order to redeploy.
